Date:    Wed, 27 Oct 93 12:24:14 -0400
From:    Otto Stolz <RZOTTO@nyx.uni-konstanz.de>
Subject: Re: Draft Swiss AntiVirus regulation

On Fri, 15 Oct 93 09:46:32 -0400 Douglas de Lacey <DEL2@phx.cam.ac.uk>
said:
> "Wer unbefugt elektronisch oder in vergleichbarer
> Weise gespeicherte oder uebermittelte Daten loescht, [...]
> wird, auf Antrag, mit der gleichen Strafe belegt."
>
> Now surely the phrase "elektronisch oder ...Weise" could qualify either
> "gespeicherte" (as [presumably] in the translation offered) or "loescht"
> (indicating that the law is against viri rather than against, say, the
> burning of floppies)? Is there something special in Swiss German which
> could distinguish between the two possibilities[...]?

Will you accept a grammatical analysis from a native (southern, but not
Swiss) speaker?

Actually, the phrase is grammatically unambiguous; yet, the difference
between the two German phrases Douglas has translated hinges on a mere
comma! Let me explain:
- - "unbefugt", "elektronisch", and "in vergleichbarer Weise" all are
  adverbs; adverbs can (as the term is suggesting :-) , and as Douglas
  has implied) qualify either a verb (including its participle forms), or
  an adjective (including its adverbial form).
- - "gespeicherte" and "gel>schte" are plural forms of past participles,
  "l>scht", and "wird ... belegt" are finite verb forms; hence all of
  these could be qualified by adverbs.
- - Several adverbs qualifying the same part of a sentence, must be
  separated by conjunctions (term??), such as "oder", or by commata.
  Thus, "elektronisch", and "in vergleichbarer Weise", are marked by
  "oder" to qualify the same part of the sentence, viz. "gespeicherte
  oder ubermittelte". (They could, indeed, interpreted to qualify
  "gespeicherte" alone, but this does not make much sense to me.)
  If the third adverb, "unbefugt" is meant to join these two in
  qualifying the same part of the sentence, you would have to connect
  it in one of two possible ways: either via a conjunction, as in
  "unbefugt oder elektronisch oder in vergleichbarer Weise", or by a
  comma, as in "unbefugt, elektronisch oder in vergleichbarer Weise".
- - If, on the other hand, "unbefugt" is meant to qualify the predicate,
  "l>scht", you have to place it within the sentence (i.e. no comma).
  There are two possible positions to place it: either before, or after,
  the object, "... gespeicherte ... Daten".

Summary:

- - "Wer unbefugt, elektronisch oder in vergleichbarer Weise gespeicherte
  oder ubermittelte Daten l>scht, ..." means either "Whoever erases
  data that have been stored or transmitted either without authorisation,
  or electronically, or in comparable ways, ..." or "Whoever, either
  without authorization, or electronically, or in comparable ways,
  erases data that have been stored or transmitted, ...". Note that this
  is *not* the proposed wording.

- - "Wer unbefugt elektronisch oder in vergleichbarer Weise gespeicherte
  oder ubermittelte Daten l>scht, ..." means "Whoever, without
  authorisation, erases data that have been stored or transmitted either
  electronically, or in comparable ways, ...". Note the missing comma
  that makes all the difference.

- - The latter meaning could less ambiguously expressed by: "Wer
  elektronisch oder in vergleichbarer Weise gespeicherte oder
  ubermittelte Daten unbefugt l>scht, ...". However, lawyers are used
  to find the qualifier "unbefugt" right after the initial "Wer".
  Thus, this essential qualifier would be prone to being overlooked
  by those professionals in this wording, even if it seems unambiguous to
  the layman...

Btw, both of Douglas' proposed translations contain the term "useless"
which is not in the German text. My translation of the whole article is:
"Whoever, without authorization, erases, modifies, or renders unusable,
electronically, or in a comparable way, stored, or transmitted, data, or
creates, promotes, offers, makes available, or circulates in any other
way, means destined for unauthorized deletion, modification, or rendering
unusable, of such data, will be inflicted with the same punishment, if a
petition is filed."

Note that, to a layman, the whole article still contains a syntactical
ambiguity (I hope I got it through to my English version): the adverb
"unbefugt" ("without authorization") could either qualify the predicate
of the first half sentence, viz. "l>scht .. macht", alone, or the
predicates of both half sentences, viz. "l>scht ... macht oder herstellt
. bringt". Hence, it is not clear whether circulating a virus (i.e. a
means destined for unauthorized modification of data) will be an offense,
or only unauthorized circulation of a virus will constitute an offense.

Whether the proposed rule is sensible, is beyond the scope of this
contribution.

Best wishes,
                    Otto Stolz <RZOTTO@DKNKURZ1.Bitnet>
                               <RZOTTO@nyx.uni-konstanz.de>

