Date:    Wed, 27 Oct 93 10:29:03 -0400
From:    padgett@tccslr.dnet.mmc.com (A. Padgett Peterson)
Subject: Virus scanning in Unix (UNIX)

>From:    "David M. Chess" <chess@watson.ibm.com>
>Subject: Re: Virus scanning for UNIX (UNIX)

>So, while it's very easy to say "well, Unix system have security /
>access control / permission bits / whatever, and this will make
>it harder to write a virus", I don't think we have any evidence
>that it really *will* make it harder.

David is correct here and as I recall (and am sure Fred will correct
me if wrong), Dr. Cohen's first virus experiments were conducted on a
VAX 11/750 running Ultrix.

There are a couple of caveats though, First, UNIX actively uses
checksum and header flags which would have to be circumvented.
Secondly, most system executables are set to 644 which means that root
privilege is necessary to write and this is much more difficult to
change than the "read-only" flag in DOS. Thirdly, not that many people
have UNIX boxes at home to play with. Fourthly, UNIX runs on many
different platforms and usually must be recompiled for each. Finally,
is is easier and just as effective under UNIX to write a worm as it is
to write a virus (there are a lot of reasons for this last one - too
many to go into here).

[Moderator's nitpick: Actually, most UNIX executables are set to 755,
not 644 (or else they wouldn't include the _execute_ bit.]

The famous "Morris Worm" targeted just two specific platforms -
VAX/Ultrix and SUN, eploiting a number of "known" weaknesses.

So the good news is that viruses are unlikely but possible. On the
other hand, a worm under Unix is both likely AND possible. A directed
attack against a given installation using a limited number of
platforms is both likely and possible. And, as I have been saying for
years, integrity management, possibly coupled with limited
functionality workstations (does every workstation *need* a C compiler
?) is what is necessary.

						Warmly,
							Padgett

