Date:    Thu, 28 Oct 93 10:35:12 -0400
From:    "David M. Chess" <chess@watson.ibm.com>
Subject: Re: Virus scanning for UNIX (UNIX)

> From:    pstemari@well.sf.ca.us (Paul J. Ste. Marie)

> Doesn't a secure file system greatly limits the potential for spead of
> viruses?  An infected program would have to be executed by root to
> spead the infection to most of the system software.

But that "most" can be a killer.  On a typical Unix machine that
has at least a few developers and/or gurus on it, there will be
a significant number of cases where someone (not root) has
execute access to programs that someone else (not root) has
write access to.  A virus can spread along this sort of
link until it gets to someone who is root, and at that point
all bets are off.

Consider a rewording of your question into the PC area:
> Doesn't the lack of networking greatly limit the potential for spread
> of viruses?  An infected program would have to be executed on a
> golden-build machine in order to get really widely distributed.

Well, sure.  But if it can spread slowly through contacts between
people who aren't building Golden Masters, it may eventually get
to a Golden Master machine, at which point baf it's shipped to
thousands of machines world-wide.  Happens all the time, sadly.
No particular reason the analogous thing couldn't happen under
Unix, if the cultural sharing patterns were right.

Sharing patterns allow viruses to spread between PCs, despite
the fact that most PCs aren't networked to each other.  Sharing
patterns in the future could allows viruses to spread between
Unix (etc) accounts and machines, despite the fact that there
are access controls in place.  Seems plausible, anyway!

