From:    padgett@tccslr.dnet.mmc.com (A. Padgett Peterson)
Subject: S-Bug virus (PC)

>Subject: Satan Bug (Virus alert) (PC)

>The following is from the October 11, 1993 issue of Network World:

>Vendors of antivirus software are scrambling to update their products
>to cope with the Satan Bug, an encrypted, polymorphic virus that is
>attacking government computer systems.

(media hype deleted)

>The encryption will also make the virus invisible to antivirus
>scanners dated before August.  *Virus scanners must open a file to
>scan it, and if your virus is in memory, the act of opening it for
>scanning will infect it.  And, if you run an infected antivirus
>scanner, nearly every executable file on the disk will be infected.:

The key here is "scanners". Integrity management software will spot it
immediately (my FreeWare CHKMEM will spot it instantly in memory using
a check added in 1990 - doesn't even require memory size input).

Second, much of the code is crude & IMHO at least two people wrote pieces.

The code owes much to the 4096/Whale but, as in any infection, there are
actually three problems involved:
a) Identification when resident in memory - easy - faulty/obvious mechanism
   used.
b) Identification in programs - relatively easy (a simple heuristic will
   find it at the expense of a few possible false positives, checksum will
   detect immediately).
c) Removal from infected programs - relatively difficult due to the
   encryption used but expect the algorithm not to be terribly difficult.
   For the moment, easiest from backups.

				Hope this helps,
						Padgett

