Date:    Wed, 27 Oct 93 10:21:37 -0400
From:    "David M. Chess" <chess@watson.ibm.com>
Subject: re: Commercial Virus Scanners in the dark??? (PC)

> From:    disruptor@pcscav.com (Chris Atkinson)

>  Question: Why are "popular `industry-known' " virus scanners such as
> McAfee's ViruScan, CPAV and NAV so slow to adopt heuristics when it's
> proven to be THE best method of virus detection...

There are two things here that I think I disagree with:

  - Essentially all reputable scanners, including IBM AntiVirus
    and the ones you mention in your posting, include some form
    of heuristic detection, even if it's only a certain amount
    of new-variant detection.  IBMAV, for instance, does fuzzy
    matching on its virus signatures, warns of files that have
    been suspiciously changed, and has an optional TSR that
    applies heuristic rules to warn of viral-looking activity.
    These are all heuristic approaches.

  - I think that when you say "heuristics" you mean the specific
    technique of statically looking at the semantics of a program
    on disk, and deciding whether or not it looks viral in some
    respect?  If that's what you mean, I don't agree that it's
    proven to be the best method of virus detection.  Could you
    give some detail on why you think so?  If done well, it can
    be reasonably good at detecting brand-new viruses, but it
    also tends to be prone to false alarms.  The heuristic
    scanners that we've looked at have had false alarm rates
    in the .1% to 1% range; this is far too high.  Accusing
    5-50 innocent files on a 5,000-file server of being infected
    would not make you very popular with a typical LAN admin!  *8)

    Even F-PROT, which has a good set of heuristics, doesn't
    use them by default (at least last time I looked), because
    of this very problem.  There are some environments where a
    high rate of false positives is bearable, but a typical
    end-user workstation or LAN server isn't among them, at
    least in our experience.

When evaluating a scanning method, it's vital to look not just
at how often it says "Yep!" at a virus, but how often it
wrongly says "Yep!" at an innocent file.  If you want a program
that's *very good* at detecting brand-new viruses, and you don't
mind a high false positive rate, I recommend the following:

     printf("The file %s is infected!!\n",argv1Y);

