disruptor@pcscav.com (Chris Atkinson) writes:

> Question: Why are "popular `industry-known' " virus scanners such as
>McAfee's ViruScan, CPAV and NAV so slow to adopt heuristics when it's
>proven to be THE best method of virus detection...

Well, I obviously cannot speak for those companies, but I'll give you
a few reasons....pick any one you like :-)

    Heuristics can be very good for finding "new" viruses, but they
    have one serious problem -  they tend to cause false alarms.  This
    is not a problem if the users have a certain level of knowledge,
    but it is a problem if your customer base includes a large number
    of novices.

    The term "THE best method of virus detection" can mean different
    things to different people, and a very large number of users don't
    really care how good their scanner is at detecting unknown viruses,
    just as long as they detect those that they might get hit by.  If
    there is no pressure from your customers, why bother ?

    The companies may provide an integrity checker - which enables them
    to claim that they will detect all new viruses too ... hence no need
    for heuristics.

    They did not buy us :-)

> It's a REAL SHAME that products such as Thunderbyte and FProt aren't as
>popular as otherwise lame and overrated products such as the
>"industry-known" scanners.

