Date:    Wed, 27 Oct 93 16:00:14 -0400
From:    "Jimmy Kuo" <cjkuo@symantec.com>
Subject: Re[2]: NAV 3.0 / MTE (PC)

Re[2]: Nav 3.0 / MTE (PC)

Bill (or is it Rochelle Altman) writes:
>We are all glad to see Jimmy Kuo's response to Jeff rice's message showing
>that NAV 3.0 now handles MTE encrypted viruses correctly.

We are glad not to have the whip cracking at our backs.  :-)

>I would be
>interested in hearing if Symantec now has the capability to identify
>the newer polymorphs (TPE,Satanbug,etc.) and how they are preparing to
>deal with others not yet in the field?

NAV 3.0 detects Girafe (TPE) using a method I call "Encypted search."
That is, we know what it looks like in its unencrypted form.  Encrypt it
to match any particular "morph".  Then search.

SatanBug (Sbug, Sat-Bug) is easy to detect.  The concern over SatanBug is
with the speed it infects and it's not easy to recover/repair an infected
file (it is recoverable through NAV 3.0's Inoculation feature).  And because
it was new, if you didn't have a sig in your scanner for this guy, you spread
the virus by invoking a scan.  So, the issue over SatanBug is not that it's
hard to detect but rather 1) it was new, 2) it spreads fast, and 3) no easy
"repair" function.  It was hard to detect only in the sense that, at the time,
few products had a signature yet.  But now, most do.  Check with your
particular vendor.  (NAV 3.0 has it.  NAV 2.1 requires the August 93 def set,
or later.)

Now to break to a tangent and also address a previous message about
Heuristics being "proven to be THE best method of virus detection..."
(quote from Data Disruptor, aka Chris Atkinson (?)).

I'll just state simply, proven by whom? since it's obviously not true.

The best way to detect a virus infection is through integrity checking.
If a correctly done check says nothing is changing on your machine, you
don't have a virus.  If something changed, and now a bunch of your other
executables are changing but you're unaware that anything should have
changed, best to be careful because you probably have a virus.

NAV 3.0 calls its integrity checking, Inoculation.  With all the viruses
you listed (MtEs, TPEs, SatanBug), Inoculation can detect AND REPAIR
everyone of them.  That's why the default settings for NAV 3.0 is to
"Inoculate Automatically."

The difference between integrity checking and scanning is that scanning
identifies particular virus strains.  Integrity checking just says,
"Hey it changed!  Did you do it on purpose?"

As for having no Heuristics, that's an ignorant statement.  We all have some
kind of heuristics.  McAfee's most well known is GENP and GENB.  Those are
heuristic definitions.  Fprot is more well known because they make it blatant.
NAV 3.0 has some heuristic definitions also.  We just don't make it obvious.
With NAV 3.0, we want to push the Inoculation technology.  (I have no
information about CPAV.)

